Title:
MorphKatz — Windows x64 polymorphic machine-code rewriter

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- MorphKatz is a Windows x64 polymorphic rewriter that mutates x86-64 machine code inside PE executables and raw shellcode into semantically equivalent but byte-different variants.  
- It targets the problem of brittle byte-pattern detections (e.g., YARA/Defender signature atoms) by applying CFG-aware instruction rewrites while preserving control flow and EFLAGS behavior.  
- The tool uses YAML rule packs for equivalence-preserving transformations, supports seeded/reproducible polymorphism, and can optionally verify correctness via re-disassembly and Unicorn basic-block emulation.  
- It includes detection feedback loops such as YARA-targeted prioritization and a Microsoft Defender (MpCmdRun) scan+bisect workflow to isolate signature anchors and drive rewrite selection.  
- It also supports “data-section morphing” that XOR-encodes signature-bearing bytes in .rdata/.data and adds a runtime decoder stub (with an anti-emulation gate) to defeat static signature hits.  
- Useful for both red teams (authorized evasion testing with reproducible diffs/reports) and blue teams (measuring rule durability, triaging signature anchors, generating polymorphic corpora for research/ML).  

Technical Focus:
- PE (Portable Executable) rewriting and hygiene (checksum, Authenticode stripping, Rich header handling)
- CFG-aware recursive disassembly and jump-table recovery (Zydis)
- Semantics-preserving instruction substitution with EFLAGS liveness/dataflow analysis
- Rule-driven rewriting via YAML packs + targeted raw-byte patch pairs
- Verification via re-disassembly and Unicorn Engine emulation
- Defender feedback loop (MpCmdRun scanning, multi-anchor bisection) and YARA-aware targeting

Use Cases:
- Generate polymorphic variants of a known binary to test AV/EDR signature robustness
- Quantify YARA rule durability across many semantically identical mutations
- Bisect and identify the exact byte windows responsible for Defender detections
- Produce reproducible “before/after” diff reports for engagement documentation
- Create controlled corpora for binary-similarity evaluation or ML classifier training

Keywords:
Windows x64, PE rewriting, polymorphic engine, x86-64, semantic equivalence, EFLAGS liveness, CFG recovery, Zydis, Unicorn Engine, LIEF, libyara, YAML rule packs, YARA targeting, Microsoft Defender, MpCmdRun.exe, signature bisection, data-section morphing, TLS callback, entry-point thunk, shellcode rewriting